uating test coverage**\\n\\nI'm considering whether the current test run coverage is complete. We're advised against running tests, but maybe we can run a tool like javap. Since there are no tests, I'm pondering why the package might be defined. In Java, a package gets defined when a class is loaded. PackageLoadedConfiguration isn't in the test source, but perhaps the Spring scanner loads it afterward. During test discovery, JUnit scans all classes, but I wonder if Gradle's scan behavior affects this. It's all a bit tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering package definitions**\\n\\nI need to find a way around the short-circuiting of getDefinedPackage by using a separate package, even if all test classes are included. If all classes in the image define packages, then any included class also defines a package, but that might not be true for the JVM. The report showing \\\"newly covered none\\\" suggests there might not even be a JVM coverage call. I wonder if our package source is loaded as a resource before findPackage. If the source path maps correctly, it should load, but this string has dots that complicate things.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering testing access**\\n\\nI’m thinking about using MethodHandles or reflection to instantiate package-private elements, but that’s not allowed. I wonder if I could put the test in the `org.springframework.boot` package to access them. The developer advised keeping tests outside of library packages, so that’s a no-go. Maybe the current test source root with underscores could be included in the user-code filter. It seems like dynamic-access coverage only tracks things within the library, though.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating JVM and metadata creation**\\n\\nI'm considering the situation with `org.springframework.boot.ssl.pem`. It seems like if there are no static references, the JVM runs the `Class.forName` method, which could lead to the creation of metadata externally for the native test build. I'm also contemplating the role of the TCK workflow and whether it triggers a native test build with metadata sourced from test resources and repository data, rather than relying on anything generated by the agent. There's quite a bit to unpack here!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_Xye1PdnClu2ib2isFkQDYUPA|fc_09bbfa71891ce904016a2520bfc0c881969ae57a9f712824b1", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot/4.0.2/src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/reachability-metadata.json", "offset": 1, "limit": 120}, "partialJson": "{\"path\":\"tests/src/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot/4.0.2/src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/reachability-metadata.json\",\"offset\":1,\"limit\":120}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1716, "output": 3261, "cacheRead": 44032, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 49009, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780818028850, "responseId": "resp_09bbfa71891ce904016a25206ee3a88196b71f3425e3a0fd9f"}}
